%N A394722 Number of transitive relations on an n-set with at most four ordered pairs.
%H A394722 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A394722/b394722.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A394722 <a href="/index/Rec#order_09">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (9,-36,84,-126,126,-84,36,-9,1).
%F A394722 a(n) = C(n,0) + C(n,1) + 10*C(n,2) + 91*C(n,3) + 503*C(n,4) + 1630*C(n,5) + 3060*C(n,6) + 3360*C(n,7) + 1680*C(n,8).
%F A394722 a(n) = A393295(n) + A349849(n).
%F A394722 a(n) = 1 + A000290(n) + A349919(n) + A349927(n) + A349849(n).
%F A394722 G.f.: (1 - 7*x + 31*x^2 - 4*x^3 + 233*x^4 + 307*x^5 + 435*x^6 + 512*x^7 + 172*x^8)/(1 - x)^9. - _Stefano Spezia_, Mar 30 2026
%e A394722 a(1) = 2 because there are only 2 transitive relations on a singleton with at most four ordered pairs, which include the empty relation and the universal relation.
%t A394722 A394722[n_] := Total[{10, 91, 503, 1630, 3060, 3360, 1680}*Binomial[n, Range[2, 8]]] + n + 1;
%t A394722 Array[A394722, 35, 0] (* or *)
